commentBody:
@Justin 
Your comment made me smile a bit as just recently I read the NYT piece about the Goffin’s cockatoo in the Gramercy Park co-op that created such a years-long stir. Perhaps some of you missed it, it’s definitely worth a read. I’ll try a free link:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/374r9duj" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/374r9duj</a>

@Evan D 

Congratulations on the personal record!

By starting these puzzles when I’m too sleepy to think clearly, I’m doing my part to raise the median solving time at xwstats.com. (I solve most Friday and Saturday puzzles in less time than this one took me.)

@Linda Jo 

That worked, thank you!

I just could not see that for the life of me. Whatever I tried, I ended up getting too many consonants in a row.

@Andrzej 
I think it's a lovely word, but also took me a while to see it even though it was the last word left. 
It makes me think of morning glories.

@Vaer 

It is a fine word indeed.

In Polish morning glory is called powój, which derives from the verb "wić", meaning to coil and to slither. In a way, the Polish word for morning glory implies its tendrilness. Tendrility? Its ability to sprout tendrils?

@Red Carpet 

Only Sunday puzzles have a title.

The title for the Wordplay columns is usually inspired by one of the clues. And Sam does it as pun play.

@Mike 

I would never be able to top that one.


🧸

@Petrol 

Lately, I’ve been spicing up the easy puzzles (and the hard ones) by starting them when I’m so sleepy I can barely keep my eyes open. After a few hours of sleep, I come back to the puzzle and I’m amused by some of the nonsense answers that I entered earlier. 

I rely on letter patterns a lot when solving (I think it was Vaer who called that “Wheel of Fortune” solving). Sometimes I don’t read all the clues, which leads to things like having RAdIO instead of RATIO and consequently being unable to make sense of TRANSLATE.

@Petrol 

I’m not so fond of it. 

Before doing the NYT puzzle last night, I solved Kameron Austin Collins’ New Yorker puzzle. There’s something going on when I solve a New Yorker Monday puzzle faster than a NYT Tuesday puzzle.

@Eric Hougland @Vaer

Love the Wheel of Fortune mini game!

Sometimes I fill most of an answer with the crosses and try to deduce the clue. My RAdIO is respectable.

@Anna 

Thanks for asking.  To be honest it has been so long but I'd have to assume that it started with the Sundays in the magazine.  When I bought the Sunday paper at the Acme the checkout clerk would always remark on the price ($5 was a lot in those days).  I'd tell her that it took me all week to read all the sections so I was getting my money's worth.  The Sunday puzzles would sometimes take all week as well. 

Two key memories:  Group family solves on the beach with our daughter's and, later, their boyfriends/husbands.   And laying in bed stumped by a Friday and my wife saying, "You have not written anything in a while".  (Grrrr!).

@Anna 

The COVID epidemic shut me and my son up alone in my house in 2020, and an incorrect diagnosis of Alzheimer's made me scramble to find a way to keep my brain functional and my vocabulary and ability to communicate intact for as long as possible.

Near brushes with death are great for forcing one to re-evaluate their lives and start making the most of each day. I highly recommend them.

@Anna  As a youngster I watched my dad do them every Sunday. Every now and then he would laugh and show me some clever wordplay that he figured out. So smart! When he collapsed and died a half- completed Sunday slipped from his hands.
 A while ago - pre internet - I picked up a Sunday and after a struggle was able to complete it.  Then my wife and I would do one every now and then.
 But I really got going during COVID.  Subscribed, and have done over 800 so far, and got my daughter hooked.

@Jane Wheelaghan 
You should visit (for instance) Texas--a football and cheerleader culture!  And that's just junior and senior high schools and colleges and universities--not just pro ball.  

(DHubby loves college football, but strongly supports only Penn State--undergrad alma mater--and any teams that battle Penn State's arch-rivals.  He ignores details like cheerleaders and the bands.  I loathe football season...)

@Bruce 

That's exactly what I mean - for many people who experienced Polaroid cameras in their lives, they evoke images and feelings, bring back memories. I appreciate that. Alas, I feel none of that myself. 

I have similar nostalgia for something related, though. The only color camera film and the supplies for developing color pictures available in Poland in the 1980s were by the DDR manufacturer Orwo. It was all really low quality, and over time the pictures faded and changed their color palette. Seeing those old, muted photos makes me feel 5 or 10 again.

@Bruce 

I just checked...you can still buy film for Polaroid cameras.

Now I'm considering what to do with that information.

@Mean Old Lady 
It is not recommended to shake a Polaroid picture, but people do it anyway.... I've done it myself.

It's like a uncontrollable compulsion to wave it in the air, lol. I think it gives one the illusion that it will dry faster.

@Lewis 

If the puzzle had been clued with Elvis OR the complete line, it might deserve a pass, but it's not, and it doesn't

BLAH.   CLUNK.  (UHs aren't strong enough.)

@JohnWM 

FWIW, xwstats.com said this puzzle was Easy, with 92% solving faster than their Tuesday average.  My experience was in line with this, with a 28% faster-than-Tuesday-average time for me.

Goes to show you that if one (or two) little things trip you up, your stats are going to be off.  After all, 8% did solve slower than usual.

@Revvv 

Keep in mind that the stats come only from those who have registered for the site, and presumably, those tend to be the more devoted solvers. 

So I’d consider their published medians as something akin to a par rating in golf. What an expert golfer or solver should expect to achieve, not the weekend duffer. Useful still to make comparisons from one puzzle to another.

@ad absurdum

Unfortunately, yes.

She's tiny and tough and loves to wrestle her uncle, older brother, and grandmother.  I see a change of activities in her future.

@Barry Ancona 

I'll have to check. 

She did a demo for us at Thanksgiving and I almost choked on my hors d'oeuvre.

@David Reiffel 
Yes! I had a Swinger back in the day, actually still have it up on a shelf on display, a beautiful piece of equipment. Of course I remember the “wet squeegee” thingy. I remember the solution it spread had a terrible smell, and one theory was that shaking would speed up the drying of that solution and lessen the time you had to smell the stuff. See:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/4mfandv7" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/4mfandv7</a>

@Stan43 

In my copy of Lexie Kahn's "The Authoritative Guide to Crossword Construction", 7th edition, page 547, 3rd paragraph, it clearly states:

 "Unless it is in service of the theme, the answer word cannot be included in the clue for *that* answer."  (Emphasis mine)

@Nancy J. 

The “you” in the clue was for a different entry than the one that had “you” in it. It just happened that they crossed. 

And there’s nothing wrong with that situation.

@A B Church 

Yes, but there was a chance that you thought you had solved the puzzle when you hadn't.

Of course, you could check your work against the key, but I never bothered to do that if everything I entered seemed correct.

@Bruce D 

Also, we don't spoil puzzles from other sources here.

SMFH.

@Steve L 
I have no issue with you calling it that. My point is that more than one interpretation is plausible and thus the OP is not being fair objecting to Sam’s use of the expression. See this from the Chicago Manual of Style:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/3dnpnvwh" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/3dnpnvwh</a>

@Renegator 

I think you’re in a distinct minority. See my earlier comment about the xwstats.com rating of Easy, in which about 99% of solvers solved faster than usual. 

Sometimes, it’s just some personal gaps in knowledge.

@Byron Yes plus I think more people didn’t vote than voted for either of them so hope they’re all going to be able to sleep with their protest votes /s.

“History sighs and repeats itself,”
and it this case got even worse.

@wendyfromboulder 

Ohh, I loved 60A, personally. Good chuckle for me!

You can change your settings, so that it doesn't move for you. On my platform, it's a blue gear icon just above the puzzle.

@Rich in Atlanta 

Interesting! I really wish there was a write up about that one, that would be interesting to read.

I like CATCHERINTHEVODKA!
